When filing a Statement of Conversion from an LLC to a Corporation in the state of Nevada, you may be required to provide certain supporting documentation to the Nevada Secretary of State. The specific documentation that may be needed can vary depending on the specific circumstances and requirements of your LLC and the nature of the conversion. Here are some common documents that may be required or useful:

1. Articles of Organization or Certificate of Formation: This document establishes the LLC's existence and provides basic information about it, such as its name, address, registered agent, and management structure.

2. Operating Agreement: The operating agreement outlines the ownership, management, and operational details of an LLC. It is not required to be filed with the state, but having it on hand may be useful during the conversion process to clarify certain issues.

3. Articles of Incorporation: This document establishes the corporation's existence and includes information such as its name, purpose, registered agent, and number of shares of stock. You will need to file this document with the Nevada Secretary of State as part of the conversion process.

4. resolutions passed by the LLC members or managers approving the conversion;
5. A statement that the LLC is involuntarily converting due to factors such as the death of a member, bankruptcy, or other causes;
6. If applicable, a statement indicating that the LLC has paid off all debts and obligations and is wound up and dissolved;
7. Any relevant contracts, leases, or agreements related to the business operations that will continue with the new corporate structure;
8. A description of the assets and liabilities of the LLC at the time of conversion; and
9. Additional documents as may be required by the Nevada Secretary of State's specific forms and instructions for filing the Statement of Conversion.

It is important to review the requirements carefully, as the specific documentation needed can vary depending on the unique circumstances of your LLC and the nature of the conversion. It is always recommended to consult with a legal professional or the Nevada Secretary of State's website for the most up-to-date and accurate information.
